Question.create!(location_title: "Taylor Valley", interesting_1: "This place is named after an Australian geologist", interesting_2: "The tan bands are sandstone layers from Beacon Supergroup, a series of sedimentary rock layers formed at the bottom of a shallow sea between 250 million and 400 million years ago", interesting_3: "", subtitle: "Antartica", photo_credit: "NASA Earth Observatory, Robert Simmon, using Landsat 8 data, USGS Earth Explorer.", info_source: "http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/IOTD/view.php?id=82524", image_url: "http://eoimages.gsfc.nasa.gov/images/imagerecords/82000/82524/taylorglacier_pho_2013_studinger_lrg.jpg", local_url: "TaylorValley", answer_description: "Taylor Valley is one of the most remote and geologically exotic places in the world. Taylor Valley and the other dry valleys are conspicuously bare. Taylor Glacier is “cold-based,” meaning its bottom is frozen to the ground below.", choice_1: "Star Dunes| Algeria", choice_2: "Nevados de Chillan| Chile-Argentina", choice_3: "Rhodes| Greece", choice_4: "Taylor Valley| Antartica", correct_choice: "4")
